tip.text: After what feels like a horrible eternity, London Fields lido is back up and running. This is the rarest of gems in London: a heated 50m outdoor pool with decent facilities to boot where inconceivably spritely speedo-clad swimmers glide up and down the lanes without losing their breath. They have swimming lessons for children and adults, a sunbathing area, cafe and swimfit sessions too. It gets super busy here in the summer and is probably best avoided on hot days.

Probably the most popular park in Hackney, this place is a mecca for all sorts of cats enjoying the weather when the sun's out. There's a lido, a cafe, a basketball court, cricket pitch and plenty of green space to stretch out in. There's also a special BBQ area where disposables are allowed before 9pm.

Itching for a rural stroll along a serene body of water? Keen to forget you're in the Big Smoke and escape to something a bit more Robin Hood? Can't face journeying out of the London boroughs? Look no further than Waltham Forest's answer to all your cabin fever fears.

Walthamstow Marsh Nature Reserve is part of Lee Valley Park and is made for lush green walks, ogling at pretty houseboats and picnicing if the weather is kind.

Vicky park is an East London mainstay - the kind of place where you'll see early morning joggers, friendly-looking dog walkers, can-sinking teenagers and anyone else who might enjoy a park. It's a huge place with plenty of different aspects: from the tree lined promenades to the football fields, tennis courts, and ponds where you can jump in a pedalo.

There are plenty of easy-access pubs around and it's also home to the excellent Pavilion Cafe, which can be very busy come the weekend. Throw in a Sunday market, and it's pretty clear that this is a wonderfully multi-talented park, perfect for a wintry walk or doing a little sport.

This massive regional park is the biggest in London - four times the size of Richmond Park. Now that's a lot of green. Its colossal size makes it ideal for woodland explorations and long, long walks - check their website for guided walking routes around the park.

There's also a plethora of activities on offer at the park: canoeing, kayaking, ice skating, golf, horse riding. It's also made up of a diverse mix of heritage sites, country parks, nature reserves, and lake and riverside trails. Make sure you bring Google Maps with you, this one's a biggie.

A glossy pic of this unique oasis is what youll find when you look up the words pure, magic and heart-warmingly beautiful in the Dojo dictionary. Yeah, our dictionary has pictures. Sitting on the old Eastern Curve railway line, entering the covert door here is akin to walking through the wardrobe to Narnia - minus the talking animals, mythical creatures and foreboding sense of danger. Instead youve got plants, wood-chippings, fairy lights and a friendly crowd of locals basking in Dalstons version of heaven.

The long, curved garden features plants, veggies and herbs; a cafe that also sells beers, wine and homemade soups; a stage for live music; and a pizza oven doing 6 pies. This is truly a community place with a wealth of programmes and workshops aimed at helping isolated people. Chilling with some pals beneath the tree-top canopy as the evening draws in is one of Londons true pleasures.

Pigs and donkeys and sheep, oh my - Hackney Farm is the primo destination to get your fill of cute, fuzzy things. Smack dab in E2, this volunteer-run project is open to all for cuddles with farmyard animals. But it isn't all about the beasts, you know. You'll also find pottery classes, drawing sessions, a cafe, and more. Or if you're feeling green, lend a hand at one of their volunteering sessions.

The conventional wisdom when in Stoke Newington is that Clissold Park is the place to go for your post-brunch, pre-yoga mooches. Whilst this is a not a bad shout by any stretch, wed personally tip the slightly wilder, beautifully overgrown Abney Park Cemetery as the premium Stokey walking spot.

Built back in 1840 as one of the Magnificent Seven garden cemeteries, its now a sprawling maze of ivy-clad tombs and overgrown pathways that lead to a massive Gothic church in the middle. It sounds spooky but its mainly dog walkers and cyclists taking the shortcut to Wholefoods.

A true community space, St Mary's Secret Garden is a public park that has been used for horticultural therapy for the past 25 years: that's healing with plants, people, and is maybe the most wholesome of uses for a shared green space.

There are woodlands, herbs, vegetables, herbaceous borders, a small pond and a greenhouse, all used and maintained by people with mental health issues, learning and physical disabilities. It's open to the public throughout the week, and we could all benefit from some of the healing power of horticulture every once in a while.

Lush and expansive, Hackney Marshes is a beautiful slice of wetlands right off Homerton Road. A Sunday stroll through the marshes with a coffee from Chatsworth Road is pure bliss - and in spring, the yellow dandelions make our hearts skip a beat.

There's also a cafe bar with a rooftop terrace, football, cricket and rugby pitches available to rent, and a lovely bunch of people called the Hackney Marshes User Group who like to protect the space and plant tings to make it look all nice and pretty for you. See? There are some good people left in the world.

This bar, restaurant and music-cum-art space next to the canal has an ethos we're right behind: an experiment in creating a community area with businesses adhering to ethical, sustainable and green business models. Think locally sourced, organic and fair trade produce sourced from organisations that don't avoid their taxes and pay the London living wage.

Alongside temporary restaurant residencies and a bar, they put on plenty of community events with live music, day festivals and other stuff all in-keeping with community spirit.

How can a garden be nomadic, we hear you ask. The answer is simple: you plant it in raised beds, to avoid ground contamination and ensure your little garden can go wherever you go - if you know someone with a van, of course. That's the spirit behind the Nomadic Community Garden currently residing in the shabby-chic pastures of Shoreditch, which invites local residents to enjoy a spot of gardening during the day, or sit back and indulge in some chill vibes and live music at night.

It features over 100 flower beds made out of pallets, kooky artsy sculptures, graffitied walls, makeshift seats by the fire and a small caff on the back of a scooter - because, well, it's Shoreditch innit. It's undeniably one of the most buzzing community spots in East London, with block parties, workshops, DJs and events going on all through summer. Volunteers are welcome any time, any day, so really you've got no excuse not to pop by and muck in.

This farm, in the heart of East London, is the perfect oasis of calm for when you're looking to escape the madness of Brick Lane on the weekend. Come for pigs, sheep, goats, lambs - you know, farm animals - and brush up on your moos and bahs.

They've got an on-site independent coffee hut and plenty of space to hang out, lovely for a tea break in the summer. Also, it's completely free, although donations are encouraged.

Yknow what Londoners can never get enough of? Big ol soggy wetlands. After 150 years of secrecy, Walthamstow Wetlands is opening its big gates to the wider public, inviting everyone down for some wholesome fun. Just a 15min hop, jump and skip from central London, find a wildlife oasis perf for some bird watching, angling or just causal strolling amongst Mother Nature. They've also got a weekly calendar of events that changes on the regs, but you can expect the likes of educational trials, home-building workshops and arts & crafts.

Entry to the grounds is free.

This is one of Hackney's best loved parks and with good reason. Sure, it might not have the space of Victoria or the hedonistic vibes of London Fields, but it has plenty else going for it. It's got tennis and basketball courts, a mini zoo with goats and the like, a deer enclosure, a lovely pond, and plenty of green grass to stretch out in. There's also Clissold House, a regal looking joint serving up pretty overpriced cakes and coffee.

One of the biggest urban parks in Europe, this is a pretty calm and tranquil area full of sports facilities, bridges, wild land and play parks around the venues that hosted the 2012 Olympics. The Aquatic Centre, The Velopark, The Copper Box and The Olympic Stadium itself can all be found here. As can various sorts jogging, cycling or generally meandering about.

This community garden has an ethos we're right behind: an experiment in creating a social space where locals can grow their own fruit and veg and generally forward the notion of community. With volunteer gardening sessions, a cafe and a licence for late night events on weekends, there are plenty of reasons to come down here. It warms the heart right up.

Just because there's a lot of inactive long-term residents here, doesn't mean there's not plenty going on all the time. This is one big nature reserve, filled with wildlife, and run by two separate charities who put on 120 free events a year, and 50 paid ones.

We're talking wild food walks, bat watching, even scything courses. Plus it's a genuinely tranquil place to get away from things when you just need to clear your noggin. It also hosts the Shuffle festival run by Danny Boyle every year. Look out for the resident celebrity cat roaming the grounds, Dr. P.

It might look like your run of the mill reservoir, but if you know the right time to go and the right things to wear, you might just swim in this reservoir. On Thursday evenings and Saturday and Sunday mornings they hold open water swimming sessions where a load of serious swimmers clad in wet suits do their thing. You need to do an induction here before taking part, so book on for that.

Also, you can also book on for introductory sailing lessons here if you want to get serious out on the water. The course duration is 2 days and the cost is a mean 165.

This is a discreet green oasis in Islington that you may well miss were you not looking down at your phone, leading you there. It's neither new nor a river, but is instead a man-made waterway that opened back in 1613 to give London some drinking water from the river Lea. Surrounded by large trees and vegetation, along with crazy nice houses, this Islington stretch of the walk is a tranquil and meditative place to take a stroll. Our tip would be to finish up at the Myddleton Arms.
